The '''Lomwe''' (Lowe) language, ''Elomwe'', also known as '''Western Makua''', is the fourth-largest language in [[Mozambique]]. It belongs with [[Makhuwa language|Makua]] in the group of distinctive Bantu languages in the northern part of the country: The Makhuwa-using area proper (Nampula, etc.) is separated by a large Lomwe-speaking area from the related eChuwabo, although eMakhuwa neighbours eChuwabo in a more coastal zone. To the south, the rather more distantly related Sena (ChiSena) should be assigned to a group with Nyanja and Chewa, while the distinct group which includes Yao, Makonde and Mwera is found to the north.<ref>''Relatório do I Seminário sobre a Padronização da Ortografia de Línguas Moçambicanas, NELIMO, Maputo, 1989.</ref> Apart from the regional variations found within eMakhuwa proper, eLomwe uses '''ch''' where '''tt''' appears in eMakhuwa orthography: for instance eMakhuwa '''mirette''' ("remedy") corresponds to eLomwe '''mirecce''', eMakhuwa '''murrutthu''' ("dead body") to eLomwe '''miruchu''', eMakhuwa '''otthapa''' ("joy") to eLomwe '''ochapa'''.
Unusual among Bantu languages is the infinitive of the verb with '''o-''' instead of the typically Bantu '''ku-''' prefix: '''omala''' (eMakhuwa) is "to finish", '''omeeela''' (also an eMakhuwa form) is "to share out".<ref>''Relatório'', as above.</ref>
A [[mutually unintelligible]] form containing elements of [[Chewa language|Chewa]], [[Malawian Lomwe]], is spoken in [[Malawi]]. Maho (2009) separates out Ngulu (Mihavane) as a separate language, close to [[Malawi Lomwe language|Malawi Lomwe]].<ref name="Guthrie"/>
