'''Nchumbulu''' is a highly endangered language that is spoken in [[Ghana]] by the [[Brong Ahafo]] region west of [[Lake Volta]] near [[Kplang language|Kaplang]] and is spoken in three villages in the area.<ref>Batibo, Herman ''Language Decline and Death in Africa: Causes, Consequences, and Challenges'' (2005)</ref><ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/language/nlu Nchumbulu [[Ethnologue]] ]</ref>
==Classification== {{Infobox language |name = Nchumbulu |nativename = |states = [[Ghana]] |speakers = 1,800 |date = 2003 |ref=e18 |familycolor = Niger-Congo |fam2 = [[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3 = [[Volta-Congo languages|Volta-Congo]] |fam4 = [[Kwa languages|Kwa]] |fam5 = [[Nyo]] |fam6 = [[Potou–Tano languages|Potou–Tano]] |fam7 = [[Tano languages|Tano]] |fam8 = [[Guang languages|Guang]] |fam9 = North |iso3 = nlu |glotto=nchu1238 |glottorefname=Nchumbulu }}
'''Nchumbulu''' is a [[Guang language]] of [[Ghana]] that is part of the North Guang subdivision of the language family.<ref>Ansah, M. A., & Agyeman, N. A. (2015). Ghana language-in-education policy: The survival of two South Guan minority dialects. In: ''Per Linguam'' 31(1), 89.</ref>
