{{Infobox Ethnic group |group = Üzemchin Mongols |image = |pop = |region1 = {{flag|Inner Mongolia}} |pop1 = |ref1 = |region2 = {{flagcountry|Mongolia}} |pop2 = 2,577 |ref2 = <ref name="mongolian">[http://www.toollogo2010.mn/doc/Main%20results_20110615_to%20EZBH_for%20print.pdf National Census 2010]</ref> |region3 = |pop3 = |ref3 = |languages = [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]] |religions = [[Tibetan Buddhism]], [[Shamanism]] , [[Atheism]] |related= [[Mongols]], [[Mongols in China]] }}
The '''Üzemchin''' ([[Mongolian language|Mongolian]]: Үзэмчин), also written '''Ujumchin''', '''Ujumucin''' or '''Ujimqin''', are a subgroup of [[Mongols]] in eastern [[Mongolia]] and [[Inner Mongolia]]. They settle mainly in [[Sergelen, Dornod|Sergelen]], [[Bayantümen, Dornod|Bayantu'men]], [[Choibalsan (city)|Choibalsan city]] of the [[Dornod Province]] and in [[Xilin Gol League]] of the [[Inner Mongolia]]. In Mongolia, Some Üzemchins migrated there from Xilin Gol immediately after China was freed from the Japanese in 1945.
The Üzemchin was included the [[Chahar Mongols|Chahar]] tumen of the six tumen eastern Mongols in [[Northern Yuan Dynasty]]. The land of Ongon-Dural, the third son of [[Bodi Alagh Khan]] of the [[Northern Yuan]] was called Üzemchin. The name probably originates from the Mongolian language word "uzem" meaning "[[raisin]]" as in "raisin pickers/collectors."
The Üzemchin language is a dialect of [[Chakhar Mongolian]].
